<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<network-security-config>
    <!--
    F-004 / Issue #31 — Cleartext HTTP enforcement is implemented at the
    OkHttp layer, NOT here. See HttpAllowlistInterceptor + HttpAllowlistHolder.

    Why base config still permits cleartext:
    Android's NetworkSecurityConfig accepts only static hostnames or IP
    literals — it cannot express CIDR ranges (RFC 1918 LAN), and the
    framework has no public API to add domains at runtime. Self-hosted
    Paperless-ngx installations on private networks (192.168.x.x, 10.x.x.x,
    user-defined ports) require cleartext; encoding every possible LAN host
    statically is infeasible.

    Runtime gate (in HttpAllowlistInterceptor):
      - HTTPS                            → pass through
      - HTTP to localhost / 127.0.0.1 / 10.0.2.2 (loopback + emulator) → pass
      - HTTP to user-accepted host       → pass + WARN log
      - HTTP to anything else            → CleartextNotAllowlistedException
                                            (IOException subclass), fail-closed
                                            before socket open / token attached

    Pre-detection accept flow (Issue #233):
    When the user types an explicit http:// URL or HTTPS detection fails
    with the HTTP fallback being interceptor-blocked, LoginViewModel
    surfaces a ServerStatus.RequiresHttpAccept state. The setup screen
    shows the HttpFallbackWarningDialog BEFORE any further network probe;
    accepting persists the host into TokenManager → HttpAllowlistHolder
    so the interceptor passes subsequent requests through. This unblocks
    the first-run case where a brand-new install could never connect to
    a LAN plain-HTTP server because the accept-dialog hung off a Success
    branch the interceptor was preventing us from reaching.
    -->
    <base-config cleartextTrafficPermitted="true">
        <trust-anchors>
            <!-- Trust system CA certificates -->
            <certificates src="system" />
            <!-- Trust user-installed CA certificates for self-signed certs -->
            <certificates src="user" />
        </trust-anchors>
    </base-config>
</network-security-config>
